'''Pacific Aviation Museum Pearl Harbor''' is a [[non-profit]] founded in 1999 to develop an aviation museum in [[Hawaii]].<ref name="japair">{{cite news|title=RARE JAPANESE AIRCRAFT RETURNS TO PEARL HARBOR.|publisher=US Fed News Service, Including US State News|year=2006|via=HighBeam Research|accessdate=March 2, 2014|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1178149591.html|subscription=yes}}</ref>  Part of Senator [[Daniel Inouye]]'s vision for a rebirth of [[Ford Island]], the museum hosts a variety of aviation exhibits with a majority relating directly to the [[attack on Pearl Harbor]] and [[World War II]].  The first section of the museum, hangar 37, opened with the museum on December 7, 2006 and features much of the museum's static exhibits.  The museum's hangars will show damage from the attacks on Pearl Harbor from December 7, 1941.

The museum has been involved in community events ranging from preservation of historical landmarks to educational tours throughout Hawai'i. The focus devoted efforts to restoring the Ford Island control tower and signed a lease with the Navy to begin repairs. Visitors to the museum gain access via [[Roberts Hawaii|tour bus]] from the [[USS Arizona Memorial|Pearl Harbor Historic Sites]] on Halawa landing or use a US Military ID card at the [[Admiral Clarey bridge]] gate. The museum has received awards for their efforts to restore historical buildings and is listed as a top 10 aviation museum on TripAdvisor.

==History==
[[Image:Ford Island Control Tower.jpg|thumb|250px|Control tower on Ford Island seen in the movies [[Tora! Tora! Tora!]] and [[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]. The tower is being restored by the Pacific Aviation Museum Pearl Harbor.]]

In 1983, the Pacific Aerospace Museum was formed inside [[Honolulu International Airport]] after pressure from the [[Hawaiian Chamber of Commerce]] to create an aviation museum in [[Hawaii]] succeeded.<ref name="pacmon2013">{{cite book|title=I'll Fly to Hawaii &mdash; A century of Aviation|author=Burl Burlingame|publisher=Pacific Monograph|year=2013|isbn=9780962922763|page=135,141}}</ref> The first phase of the museum opened in 1991 and was founded by [[Frank Der Yuen]].<ref name="pacmon2013"/> The idea for the Pacific Aviation Museum began on the anniversary of the [[Victory over Japan Day|victory over Japan]] in 1995.<ref name="honadv1997">{{cite news|title=Museum plan taking flight|publisher=The Honolulu Advertiser|author=Scott Ishikawa|date=November 2, 1997|page=A27}}</ref>  After the [[September 11 attacks]], the Pacific Aerospace Museum operation was suspended by the state and finally removed two years later.<ref name="pacmon2013" />  A few of the exhibits were salvaged by the Pacific Aviation Museum's Pearl Harbor foundation as well as responsibility for the education and scholarship programs.<ref name="pacmon2013" />

Prior to the completion of the [[Admiral Clarey Bridge]] in 1998, access to [[Ford Island]] was provided via [[ferry boat]] only to those residing on Ford Island and their guests.<ref name="honadv1997"/> Senator Inouye proposed a $500,000,000 "rebirth" of Ford Island through special legislation 2814 U. S. Code<ref>{{UnitedStatesCode|10|2814}}</ref> to authorize the Navy to sell land to fund the rebirth.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2007/09/02/news/story05.html|title=A Reborn Ford Island Hosts Military Minds|first=Gregg K. |last= Kakesako|date=2 September 2007|work=Star-Bulletin|accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref><ref name="grekak2">{{cite news|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/98/04/14/news/story6.html|title=Bridge Opens Path to Ford Island Development|first=Gregg K. |last=Kakesako|work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|date=14 April 1998|accessdate=13 February 2014}}</ref><ref name="honstar2002" />  The plan included 500 new homes for Navy personnel, a new child development center, a new Navy lodge, and the Pacific Aviation Museum Pearl Harbor.<ref name="grekak2" /><ref name="honstar2002" />  The original museum was called the Military Aviation Museum of the Pacific.<ref name="honstar2002">{{cite news|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2002/12/01/news/index8.html|title=Ford Island fund-raiser set|author=Gregg K. Kakesako|publisher=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|date=December 1, 2002|accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref>  The foundation sought funds to raise the original $46 million goal from various sources including the US [[Hawaii|State of Hawaii]], the [[United States Congress]], the [[United States Navy]], and fundraising dinners.<ref name="honstar2002" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=5092|title=Heroes Help Raise Funds for Military Aviation Museum in Hawaii|date=December 12, 2002|author=Sandra Sagisi|publisher=Military Aviation Museum of the Pacific Public Affairs|accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref>  It received support from former US [[astronaut]] [[Captain (naval)|Captain]] [[Walter Schirra]].<ref name="honstar2002" />  While executive director of the [[San Diego Air & Space Museum]], Allan Palmer was hired by the [[United States Air Force]] to conduct a feasibility study on an aviation museum in Hawaii and then hired as its executive direction and chief executive operating officer.<ref name="honadv1997" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wphsalumni-1961.com/more/a_palmer.html|title=Commander Palmer|publisher=Winter Park High School Alums - Class of 1961|accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref><ref name="stabul2006">{{cite web|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2006/03/26/news/story07.html|title=Vintage warplanes will join the displays at a museum honoring Pacific air combat|author=Gregg K. Kakesako|date=March 26, 2006|publisher=Star-Bulletin|accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref>

A groundbreaking ceremony was held March 21, 2006 for the $75,000,000 construction of the museum.<ref name="fednew" /><ref name="vwfmag" />  It opened on December 7, 2007 on the 65th anniversary of the [[attack on Pearl Harbor]].<ref name="plapil">{{cite journal|title=Pearl Harbor Museum|publisher=Plane and Pilot|year=2005|via=HighBeam Research|accessdate=March 2, 2014|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1032043701.html|subscription=yes}}</ref>  Its board consists of former [[United States president]] [[George H.W. Bush]], [[brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]] [[Chuck Yeager]], and formerly [[brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]] [[Paul Tibbets]].<ref name="plapil" />  The museum occupies hangers 37, 54, and 79 on [[Ford Island]] and covers 16 acres.<ref name="fednew">{{cite news|title=AVIATION RETURNS TO FORD ISLAND|publisher=US Fed News Service, Including US State News|year=2006|via=HighBeam Research|accessdate=March 2, 2014|author=Journalist 2nd Class Devin Wright|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1009130751.html|subscription=yes}}</ref>  In 2012, the Pacific Aviation Museum Pearl Harbor was named an affiliate of the [[Smithsonian Institution]] as part of the [[Smithsonian Affiliations]] program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnetwork.com/pacific-aviation-museum-named-affiliate-of-smithsonian/|title=Pacific Aviation Museum named affiliate of Smithsonian|date=September 20, 2012|publisher=KHON2|accessdate=May 4, 2014}}</ref>  On April 4, 2013, the museum received its millionth visitor.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fox40.com/2013/04/04/modesto-family-the-millionth-visitor-to-hawaiis-pearl-harbor-museum/|title=Modesto Family the Millionth Visitor to Hawaii<U+2019>s Pearl Harbor Museum|author=Ian McDonald|publisher=Fox40|date=April 4, 2013|accessdate=March 12, 2013}}</ref>

===Facilities===
[[File:RAAF F-111C in front of Hangar 37.jpg|thumb|250px|The arrival of a [[Royal Australian Air Force]] [[F-111]]C in front of hangar 37.]]
Due to its historical significance, as the location of the first radio alert of the [[attack on Pearl Harbor]], the museum plans to spend over $7,500,000 repairing the Ford Island control tower.<ref name="stanew">{{cite news|title=PACIFIC AVIATION MUSEUM PRESERVES HISTORIC FORD ISLAND TOWER|publisher=States News Service|year=2011|accessdate=March 14, 2014|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-250482481.html|subscription=yes|via=HighBeam Research}}</ref>  It was registered as a category 1 structure in the 1978 Pearl Harbor Naval Base Historic Preservation Plan and is being restored by Kiewit Building Group; the same contractor who built the museum.<ref name="stanew" />  The 70-year-old {{convert|158|ft}} tower suffers from deteriorating steel stairs, landing, and beams that require repair or replacement.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.hawaiimagazine.com/blogs/hawaii_today/2011/2/25/restoration_Pearl_Harbor_Ford_Island_control_tower|title=Restoration work begins at historic Pearl Harbor air control tower|date=February 25, 2011|author=Catherine E. Toth|accessdate=March 14, 2011|publisher=Hawai'i Magazine}}</ref>  A grant through the United States Department of Defense appropriations for the stabilization and restoration of a historical landmark was given to the museum for $3,800,000 which provided the initial funds to start the project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://generalaviationnews.com/2011/12/11/control-dedication-part-of-pearl-habor-anniversary-ceremonies/|title=Control dedication part of Pearl Habor anniversary ceremonies|author=Janice Wood|date=December 11, 2011|accessdate=March 14, 2014|publisher=General Aviation News}}</ref>  The control tower, as well as the runway, has been designated a national historic landmark since 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.modelairplanenews.com/blog/2012/09/12/pearl-harbors-historic-runway-to-be-covered-with-solar-panels/|title= Pearl Harbor<U+2019>s Historic Runway to be Covered with Solar Panels|author=Debra Cleghorn|publisher=Model Airplane News|date=September 12, 2012|accessdate=May 4, 2014}}</ref>  In 2010, records filed with Congress shows that defense firms had donated nearly $449,000 to the museum during efforts to raise money to restore the tower.<ref name="kermur">{{cite news|url=http://www.civilbeat.com/articles/2013/05/06/18949-how-lobbyist-dollars-helped-save-the-pearl-harbor-tower/|title=How Lobbyist Dollars Helped Save The Pearl Harbor Tower|author=Kerry Murakami|publisher=Honolulu Civil Beat|date=May 6, 2013|accessdate=March 12, 2014}}</ref>  The tower was considered a personal issue for Senator Inouye and many of these donations were made in his memory.<ref name="kermur" />  The tower was featured in the films ''[[Tora! Tora! Tora!]]'' and ''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/20110226_makeover_takes_flight.html|publisher=Star Advertiser|title=Officials aim to complete the $7.5M Ford Island Control Tower restoration before the 70th anniversary of Pearl Harbor's bombing|author=Gordon Y.K. Pang|date=February 26, 2011|accessdate=March 14, 2014}}</ref>

Hangar 37, a former seaplane hangar and one of the few survivors of the attack on Pearl Harbor, was the first hanger developed for the museum.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pacific Aviation Museum at Pearl Harbor|url=http://www.hawaiiactivities.com/en/hawaii/oahu/a/8180|date=31 July 2013|publisher=Hawaii Activities.com}}<!--NOTE: Content has changed since the cited date.--></ref>  The {{convert|7.25|acre}} facility consists of nine exhibits, a movie theater, flight simulators, a store and a restaurant.<ref name="vwfmag">{{cite news|title=Pacific Aviation Museum to Open|publisher=VFW Magazine|year=2006|via=HighBeam Research|accessdate=March 2, 2014|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1201515851.html|subscription=yes}}</ref>  The renovation cost was $11,000,000 and was raised by federal and state grants and through donations by local corporations.<ref name="vwfmag" />  Built in 1939 and at over {{convert|87000|sqft}}, Hangar 79 is the restoration hangar but also contains many of the museums exhibits including the [[flying tigers]] exhibit, [[MiG Alley]] exhibit, and various helicopters, jets, and civil aircraft.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/16170649/hundreds-come-together-for-pacific-aviation-museum-fundraiser|title=Hundreds come together for Pacific Aviation Museum fundraiser|author=Ben Gutierrez|date=December 1, 2011|accessdate=March 14, 2011|publisher=Hawai'i News Now}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=Record-Breaking Aircraft Known as "Missile With a Man in It" Lands at Pacific Aviation Museum Pearl Harbor|url=https://www.ereleases.com/pr/recordbreaking-aircraft-missile-man-lands-pacific-aviation-museum-pearl-harbor-146787|publisher=e-releases|date=May 30, 2013}}</ref><ref name="kribor">{{cite web|url=http://geekmom.com/2013/04/pearl-harbor-historic-sites/|title=Visiting the Pearl Harbor Historic Sites|author=Kris Bordessa|publisher=Geeky States of America|date=April 1, 2013|accessdate=March 12, 2014}}</ref>  The hangar's glass windows are still riddled with bullet holes from Japanese aircraft from the day of the attack.<ref name="kribor" />  [[Tawani Foundation]] donated $82,500 for the renovation of Hangar 79.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tawanifoundation.org/files/2011-Tawani-Foundation-Annual-Report-FINAL.pdf|title=2011 Annual Report|publisher=tawanifoundation}}</ref>

==Exhibits==
[[File:Boeing N2S-3 Stearman (6182257643).jpg|thumb|250px|Boeing Stearman Model 75 flown by former President George H.W. Bush]]
In 2009, former [[McDonalds]] CEO [[Fred L. Turner]] sponsored the restoration of a [[Douglas SBD Dauntless]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/fred-l-turner-mcdonalds-honorary-chairman-and-former-ceo-passes-away-nyse-mcd-1743118.htm|title=Fred L. Turner, McDonald's Honorary Chairman and Former CEO, Passes Away|publisher=McDonald's|date=January 7, 2013|accessdate=February 28, 2014}}</ref>  The [[Boeing-Stearman Model 75|Boeing N2S-3 Stearman]] used by former [[President of the United States|President]] [[George H.W. Bush]] for flight training and used for his first solo flight is an exhibit at the museum.<ref name="epihis" />

The remains of the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] [[A6M2]] Zero "B11-120" from the carrier [[Japanese aircraft carrier Hiry<U+016B>|Hiryu]] piloted by [[Japanese Airforce#Enlisted|Airman First Class]] Shigenori Nishikaichi, who [[Niihau Incident|crash landed]] on [[Ni'ihau]] after the second wave of the [[attack on Pearl Harbor]], are stored at the museum.<ref name="islamb">{{cite web|url=http://theislandambler.com/2013/02/02/the-pacific-aviation-museum-part-2-the-niihau-incident/|date=February 2, 2013|accessdate=February 28, 2014|title=The Pacific Aviation Museum <U+2013> Part 2 <U+2013> The Ni<U+2019>ihau Incident}}</ref>  It is displayed exactly as it was after the crash.<ref name="letsgo">{{cite book|title=Let's Go Hawaii 5th Edition|author=Let's Go, Inc.|editors=Jessica Lane Lucier, Evelyn Z. Hsieh|publisher=Macmillan|year=2008|page=448|isbn=9780312385798}}</ref>  The remains of the tractor used to create trenches to prevent such a landing are stored at the museum.<ref name="islamb" />  The trenches were created after the island was warned that the Japanese had planned to use the island as a forward operating base.<ref>{{cite news|title=ROBINSON FAMILY VISITS NI'IHAU EXHIBIT AT PACIFIC AVIATION MUSEUM|publisher=US Fed News Service, Including US State News|year=2007|via=HighBeam Research|accessdate=March 14, 2014|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1295224781.html|subscription=yes}}</ref>

A Japanese A6M2-21 Zero similar to the aircraft used in the attack on Pearl Harbor was salvaged in 1968 and restored to flying condition in 1985.<ref name="japair" />  Originally, it flew with the Japanese air group 201 in the [[Solomon Islands]].<ref name="epihis">{{cite news|title=PACIFIC AVIATION MUSEUM - EPICENTER OF HISTORY|publisher=US Fed News Service, Including US State News|year=2007|via=HighBeam Research|accessdate=March 14, 2014|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1226948481.html|subscription=yes}}</ref>  It was sold to the [[Confederate Air Force]] for use in air shows and later sold to the museum in 2006.<ref name="japair" />

[[File:Swamp Ghost at Pacific Aviation Museum Pearl Harbor.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Swamp Ghost]] restoration at the Pacific Aviation Museum Pearl Harbor]]  On April 11, 2013, the remains of a B-17 bomber arrived at the Pacific Aviation Museum Pearl Harbor almost 70 years after avoiding destruction during the attack on Pearl Harbor.<ref name="wilcol">{{cite news|title=WWII bomber arrives at isle aviation museum|author=William Cole|publisher=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/breaking/202375641.html?id=202375641 |page=B3|date=April 11, 2013}}</ref>  The restoration project is expected to cost $5,000,000.<ref name="wilcol" />  The plane, called "[[Swamp Ghost (B-17)|Swamp Ghost]]", was supposed to fly to Hickam Field on December 7, 1941 but was delayed due to engine trouble and avoided the attack.<ref name="wilcol" />  Later, it was used in the February 22, 1942 [[Bombing of Rabaul (1942)|bombing of Rabaul]].  After the bombing, the plane was attacked by nine Japanese fighters on its return to base, was struck on the wing, and crashed in marsh water.<ref name="wilcol" /><ref name="kitv" />  The plane remained there for 64 years, earning its nickname, and the wreckage was used as a navigational aide.<ref name="wilcol" />  It appeared in [[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]] in 1992 and several attempts were made to recover the aircraft, but it was not successfully recovered until 2006 and arrived back in the United States in 2010.<ref name="wilcol" />  It was purchased by the museum in 2011. It was delivered in seven separate shipment containers and is being restored outside of hangar 79.<ref name="wilcol" /><ref name="kitv">{{cite news|url=http://www.kitv.com/news/hawaii/Historic-B17-Flying-Fortress-finds-home-at-Ford-Island/19705292|title=Historic B17 Flying Fortress finds home at Ford Island|publisher=KITV|date=April 10, 2013|accessdate=March 12, 2014}}</ref>

In June 2012, the museum debuted a {{convert|10|ft|m|abbr=yes}} tall, {{convert|40|ft|m|abbr=yes}} wide diorama of the [[Battle of Midway]].<ref name="chitri2012">{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-04-26/news/ct-met-wwii-diorama-20120426_1_diorama-glenview-man-midway|title=Glenview man brings Battle of Midway to life in diorama|author=Jeff Danna|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=April 26, 2012|accessdate=May 4, 2014}}</ref>  The diorama was commissioned in 2008 for $400,000 on the advice of Turner and took three years to complete by former US Navy pilot Karl Lau.<ref name="chitri2012" />

