===''East, Wind, Rain''===
In 2008, the [[Hawaii Pacific University]] documentary and corporate video class completed development of a 12-minute film titled ''East, Wind, Rain'' to replace the older film shown to visitors at the museum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www3.hpu.edu/kalamalama/archive/3209/SUB/Front01.htm|title=The HPU Documentary and Corporate Video class, also known as Video III, is celebrating two recent achievements|author=Jennifer Ching|date=November 4, 2008|accessdate=May 7, 2014|publisher=Kalamalama, the HPU Student Newspaper}}</ref>  The film explains the surprise attack on Pearl Harbor to museum guests and won the 2010 Pixie Gold Award from American Pixel Academy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pixieawards.com/downloads/pixie-previous-winners.pdf|year=2010|title=Pixie Previous Winners|publisher=American Pixel Academy|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref>

==Public Reception==
[[File:Ford Island photovoltaic panels concept.png|thumb|250px|Conceptual design for photovoltaic panels covering the historic runway on [[Ford Island]].]]
[[File:Pacific Aviation Museum Barnstorming program.jpg|thumb|250px|''Barnstorming'' program]]
[[File:Pearl Harbor Historic Sites.jpg|thumb|250px|Sign out in front of the Pearl Harbor Historic Sites at Halawa Landing on O'ahu, Hawaii]]

===Controversies===
In 2013, the Navy was concerned about plans by the museum to host 1,500 Chinese nationals from [[Amway#Amway China|Amway China]] on Ford Island, as it remains an active military installation, who were particularly interested in the [[Flying Tigers]] exhibit.<ref name="wilcol">{{cite web|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/s?action=login&f=y&id=187705171&id=187705171|title=Chinese visitors' tour of museum puts Navy on edge|author=William Cole|date=January 21, 2013|accessdate=February 28, 2014|publisher=Star Advertiser}}</ref>  Despite these concerns, the Navy approved the event and erected a {{convert|6|ft}} tall fence.<ref name="wilcol" /><ref>{{cite news|author=William Cole|title=Fence Restricts Chinese Visitors at Museum|publisher=Honolulu Star - Advertiser|year=2013|via=HighBeam Research|accessdate=March 14, 2014|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2881450291.html|subscription=yes}}</ref>

In March 2013, the museum's online ticketing service was hacked, the museum's service provider, Vendini, believed that none of the data of its customers was accessed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pacific Aviation Museum's online ticketing service hacked|url=http://pearlcity.hawaiinewsnow.com/news/news/170933-pacific-aviation-museums-online-ticketing-service-hacked|author=HawaiiNewsNow Web Staff|publisher=Hawaii News Now|date=June 8, 2013|accessdate=March 12, 2014}}</ref>

In June 2013, the museum fought the US Navy's plan to install 60,000 [[Photovoltaics|photovoltaic panels]] over 28 acres on the Ford Island runway.<ref name="wilcol2013">{{cite news|url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/s?action=login&f=y&id=211343851&id=211343851|title=Navy halts move for solar project on historic runway|date=Jun 13, 2013|publisher=Star Advertiser|author=William Cole|accessdate=March 12, 2014}}</ref>  The Navy had intended to comply with Congressional and Defense Department mandates to reduce dependence on fossil fuels and offset the cost of Hawaiian energy costs, which are the highest in the United States.<ref name="wilcol2013" />  The plan deviated from a 2009 proposal which would use the panels to define the historic runway in favor of panels which would produce twice the power.<ref name="mcctri2012">{{cite news|title=Buffeted by opposition, Navy blinks on solar site|publisher=McClatchy-Tribute Regional News|author=William Cole|date=October 1, 2012}}</ref>  The Navy offered the museum $250,000 toward renovation of the control tower's elevator in exchange for their support of the plan which the museum declined.<ref name="mcctri2012" />  It organized an internet campaign to oppose the plan based on historical significance.<ref name="wilcol2013" />  Instead, the Navy decided to install the panels on existing structures around Pearl Harbor.<ref name="wilcol2013" />

===Community involvement===
In 2008, the museum received a grant from [[BAE Systems]] to fund its ''Barnstorming'' program to build wind tunnels and plane props that will tour local schools to teach aerospace education to sixth graders.<ref name="jenbla">{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/blog/2013/05/pacific-aviation-museum-seeks-sponsors.html|title=Pacific Aviation Museum seeks sponsors to help kids program fly on Neighbor Islands|author=Jenna Blakely|publisher=Pacific Business News|date=May 3, 2013|accessdate=March 12, 2014}}</ref>  In 2012, the program was credited with teaching 3,500 students from 40 schools.<ref name="jenbla" />

In 2013, the U.S. State Department awarded the museum the "Museums Connect" grant for the "''Past to Present: U.S. -Sino Bridge of Connections''" program.<ref name="hsta">{{cite news|url=http://www.hsta.org/index.php/news/pacific-aviation-museum-faciliates-cultural-exchange-and-leanring-project-f|title=Pacific Aviation Museum bridges cultural exchange project for Kaiser students|publisher=Hawaii State Teachers Association|date=January 7, 2013|accessdate=February 28, 2014}}</ref>  The program allowed students from [[Henry J. Kaiser High School (Hawaii)|Kaiser High School]] to participate in a cultural heritage exchange with students in [[Chengdu]], [[China]] and conduct research into 1940s [[American-Chinese relations#History of Republic of China and the USA relations|American-Chinese relations]].<ref name="hsta" />

===Tourism===
During the [[Budget sequestration in 2013|2013 federal budget sequestration]] in the United States, the Pacific Aviation Museum Pearl Harbor received an increase in tourists, due to limited ferry trips to the [[USS Arizona Memorial|USS ''Arizona'' Memorial]] which are operated by active duty [[United States Navy]] personnel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pacific/blog/morning_call/2013/04/battleship-missouri-other-pearl.html?page=all|title=Battleship Missouri, other Pearl Harbor sites benefit from sequestration|author=Stephanie Silverstein|publisher=Pacific Business News|date=April 26, 2013|accessdate=March 12, 2014}}</ref>  Because Ford Island is still part of the active military base [[Joint Base Pearl Harbor-Hickam]], tourists gain access via the [[National Park Service]]'s Halawa Landing, now known as the Pearl Harbor Historic Sites, for tickets to the museum and then are transported via tour bus onto the installation for the museum and the USS ''Missouri''.<ref>{{cite web|title=NAVY TRANSFERS HALAWA LANDING TO NATIONAL PARK SERVICE|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1185453351.html|via=Highbeam|subscription=yes|date=April 7, 2006|publisher=US Fed News Service|accessdate=May 5, 2014}}</ref>

==Recognition and awards==
Pacific Aviation Museum Pearl Harbor was listed as the eighth top aviation attraction in the United States by [[TripAdvisor]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.tripadvisor.com/PressCenter-i314-c1-Press_Releases.html|title=TripAdvisor Airs Out America's Top 10 Aviation Attractions|publisher=TripAdvisor|date=August 5, 2010|accessdate=March 12, 2014}}</ref>  In 2007, the museum was awarded a preservation award from the Historic Hawaii foundation for "a specific project that preserved, rehabilitated or restored a historic building, object, site or district" in the redevelopment of hangar 37.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://historichawaii.org/awards/previous-preservation-award-winners/|title=2007 Preservation Honor Award Winners|year=2007|publisher=Historic Hawaii Foundation|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref>

